>, <i>atte nore</i> ‘at the riverbank or hillside’, or a habitational name from a place called with this phrase, such as Nore Hill in Eartham (Sussex), Nower Wood in Headley (Surrey), Nore Farm in Bramley (Surrey), or Nower Hill in Pinner (Middlesex). Compare   Oare  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Oare","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>ore</i> ‘(river)bank’ (Old English <i>ōra</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places (in Kent, Berkshire, Wiltshire, and Somerset) named with this word."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Nowers was born about 1279, in Knossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Robert Nowers. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1279–":"umbes 1279–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1248":"1248","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","about 1279":"umbes 1279","Knossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Knossington, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom